He signalled that reducing access to guns is in his sights.The killings are believed to be linked to an apparent turf war between gangs of illegal miners.Initially police discovered six bodies with apparent gunshot wounds near a railway line on Sunday.Today eight more bodies were discovered in the same area.The discovery of these bodies comes at a time when police generals are meeting for two days at a strategic session in Mpumalanga deliberating on operational interventions and measures to reduce crime.The proliferation of firearms in South Africa is under discussion following the announcement made by the Minister of Police Nkosinathi Nhleko of a firearm amnesty period which begins on April 1.Phahlane said the provincial commissioner of Gauteng Lieutenant General Deliwe de Lange and her management team are overseeing the investigation into these murders."We will wait for the investigation to advance and the victims to be identified before speculating on a motive."Communities can be assured that the South African Police Service remains committed to further reducing the levels of serious crime and we are presently focusing on refining our crime prevention and combating operational plans " said the Acting National Commissioner.